        "summary": "Agent 12: Final review complete — all 254 tests pass, TypeScript compiles cleanly, no issues found. Architecture is consistent and correct.",
        "detail": "## Final Review Summary\n\n### Compilation & Tests\n- TypeScript compiles cleanly (`tsc --noEmit`)\n- All 254 tests pass across 17 test files\n- No TODO/FIXME/HACK comments in source or tests\n\n### Architectural Consistency Review\n\n**Adapters (Email, SMS, Webhook)** — all follow identical pattern:\n- Pluggable transport with InMemory* default for testing\n- Constructor options with sensible defaults\n- Never-throw contract: errors returned in NotificationResult\n- getSent*/clearSent* convenience methods delegating to InMemory* transport\n\n**Preferences** — per-channel support for all 3 channels:\n- Email: enabled, frequency, per-category opt-in/out\n- SMS: enabled, per-category opt-in/out (no frequency — always immediate)\n- Webhook: enabled, per-category opt-in/out (no frequency — always immediate)\n- Backward compatible: sms/webhook fields optional, defaults to all-enabled\n\n**History** — captures all notification paths:\n- 'sent' for successful delivery\n- 'failed' for adapter errors\n- 'suppressed' for preference-blocked or no-adapter scenarios\n\n**Event-driven architecture** — consistent:\n- OrderService, UserService emit events via EventBus\n- NotificationService subscribes to EventBus events\n- No direct service-to-service calls for notifications\n- CallbackRegistry exists as dead code (pre-existing utility, not exported, not used)\n\n**Dispatch ordering** — serialized via promise chain queue in NotificationService\n\n### Known Limitations\n1. `handleOrderStatusChanged` uses `event.order.userId` (a user ID) as email recipient. The `DefaultRecipientResolver` can't resolve user IDs to emails, so status change emails fail silently unless a custom RecipientResolver is injected.\n2. `in-app` is defined in `NotificationChannel` but has no adapter — it's an extension point for future work.\n3. `CallbackRegistry` still exists as dead code in `src/utils/callback-registry.ts` (pre-existing, not exported from index, not used anywhere).\n4. Notification ordering is per-service-instance only — no cross-instance guarantees in distributed scenarios.",
